Reasoning trace: this is the three-pass expansion pipeline for the stenography macro system: it turns parsed `Entry` ASTs into `TypedEntry` records that both stroke- and text-renderers consume downstream. Depending on this subtree buys you `expand_dict`, the single orchestrated entry point; nothing outside should need to call the individual passes unless it explicitly wants partial expansion (e.g. type-checking without line-flag variants).

The pipeline is strictly ordered and each pass's output is the next pass's required input shape — this is the core coupling across the whole directory. `counts.rs` (Pass A) resolves `%d`/`%(EXPR)`/`%[...]` repeat and count chunks into `ExpandedEntry`, deliberately leaving `%t`, `%b`, braces, and landings untouched. `append.rs` (Pass B) consumes that and resolves `%t` type slots into `TypedEntry`, using `fill.rs` as its substitution primitive layer (fill.rs never decides *which* fillings to apply, only performs the splice) and `types.rs` as the source of the `TypeSet`/`TypeOptions` type pool `@type` entries produce. After Pass B, `family.rs` does a whole-batch correction pass over `terminal` flags (a prefix-family entry is never terminal if a longer sibling stroke exists), and only then does `lineflag.rs` run, because it reads the now-finalized `terminal` field to decide which entries get a one-liner `U`-variant. `mod.rs` enforces this exact order (family-fix before line-flag) and is the only place that should be re-ordered if pipeline semantics change.

`ExpandedEntry` and `TypedEntry` (defined in `mod.rs`) are the shared wire format between passes — any field rename (`terminal`, `stroke`, `template`) requires lockstep updates in `family.rs`'s prefix-matching, `lineflag.rs`'s eligibility check, and `append.rs`'s step construction. `TypeDef`/`TypeOptions` (types.rs) are the second shared contract, consumed by both `append.rs` and `fill.rs`; the `no_arg` and `free_type` flags on `TypeDef` are easy to break silently since both files branch on them independently. Errors from every pass funnel into the shared `ExpandError` from `crate::error`, with `expand_dict`/`expand_all`/`expand_counts` failing fast on the first bad entry rather than collecting all errors — a consistent invariant across the whole pipeline.

A typical cross-file change starts either in `types.rs` (if the `@type` grammar or arity rules change) or in `mod.rs` (if pass ordering or the intermediate structs change) and ripples outward from there.